<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
VI. Best Available Control Measures
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
A. Requirement for BACM
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
There are two circumstances, as discussed earlier, under which a moderate PM&hyph;10 nonattainment area may be reclassified
as serious. First, an area may be reclassified whenever EPA determines that the PM&hyph;10 NAAQS cannot practicably
be attained by the statutory attainment date.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=5 f=1 -->
28
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Such a determination may be made before the attainment date if a review of the SIP for an area shows that RACM, including
RACT, will not practicably bring the area into attainment or if delays in adopting, submitting, and implementing
SIP requirements form a basis for EPA to conclude that an area cannot practicably attain the NAAQS by the statutory
attainment date. The second circumstance is when the area is reclassified by operation of law upon a determination
by EPA that the area has failed to attain the NAAQS on schedule (see section 188(b)).
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<FOOTNOTE>
<FOOTNAME>
<!-- PJG ITAG l=28 g=1 f=1 -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=28 g=5 f=1 -->
28
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

</FOOTNAME>
<!-- PJG ITAG l=28 g=1 f=1 -->
The statutory attainment date for the initial group of areas designated nonattainment by operation of law upon enactment
of the 1990 Amendments, under section 107(d)(4), is December 31, 1994.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
</FOOTNOTE>

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Section 189(b) establishes additional control requirements for PM&hyph;10 nonattainment areas that are reclassified
as serious by EPA. Under section 189(b)(1)(B), States must submit SIP revisions which provide for implementation
of the BACM for PM&hyph;10 emissions in such areas. These SIP revisions must be submitted to EPA within 18 months after
an area is reclassified and must assure that the measures are implemented no later than 4 years after the area is reclassified
as serious (see section 189(b) (1) and (2)).
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The EPA believes the requirement to implement BACM in serious PM&hyph;10 nonattainment areas should, in one respect,
be interpreted similarly to the comparable requirement to implement RACM in moderate PM&hyph;10 nonattainment
areas. Section 172(c)(1), which applies to all nonattainment areas, states that part D RACM shall include ``such
reductions in emissions from existing sources in the area as may be obtained through the adoption, at a minimum, of
reasonably available control technology&blank;*&blank;*&blank;*.'' Thus, moderate PM&hyph;10 nonattainment
area RACM plans, which are submitted to meet the requirements of section 189(a)(1)(C), must include provisions ensuring
the adoption of RACT (see 57 FR 13540, column 1).
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
For moderate PM&hyph;10 areas reclassified as serious, the nonattainment control requirements (i.e., RACM) are
carried over and elevated to a higher level of stringency (i.e., BACM). So, by analogy, just as RACM includes RACT,
in the same way, BACM includes BACT.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=5 f=1 -->
29
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Thus, just as moderate PM&hyph;10 SIP revisions when implementing RACM under section 189(a)(1)(C) must provide
for the adoption of RACT, similarly, PM&hyph;10 SIP revisions under section 189(b)(1)(B), implementing BACM in
serious PM&hyph;10 nonattainment areas, must include provisions ensuring the adoption of BACT. This point was explicitly
addressed in the House Committee Report: ``Serious areas must include in their submission provisions to require
that the best available control measures for the control of PM&hyph;10 emissions are implemented no later than 4 years
after the area is classified or reclassified as serious. Such provisions must include the application of the best
available control technology to existing stationary sources'' (H.R. Rep. No. 490, 101st Cong., 2nd Sess. 266&hyph;67
(1990)).
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<FOOTNOTE>
<FOOTNAME>
<!-- PJG ITAG l=28 g=1 f=1 -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=28 g=5 f=1 -->
29
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

</FOOTNAME>
<!-- PJG ITAG l=28 g=1 f=1 -->
Even without the RACM analogy, the best available technological control measures by their plain terms are a subset
of the universe of best available control measures.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
</FOOTNOTE>

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Although section 189(b)(1)(B) requires BACM (including BACT) to be implemented in serious PM&hyph;10 nonattainment
areas, the Act does not define either BACM or BACT for PM&hyph;10 nonattainment purposes. Where a statute is silent
or ambiguous with respect to the meaning of a statutory term, the agency is authorized to adopt an interpretation reasonably
accommodated to the purpose of the statutory provisions.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=5 f=1 -->
30
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 In considering how to interpret the provisions requiring BACM (including BACT) for serious PM&hyph;10 nonattainment
areas, EPA has looked at several factors: The way in which similar terms have been historically interpreted in other
sections or titles of the Act, the ordinary grammatical usage associated with the word ``best,'' and the overall structure
and purpose of title I of the statute.
