<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Administration of tests for students whose native language is not English or for persons with disabilities. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Students whose native language is not English. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
For a student whose native language is not English and who is not fluent in English, the institution shall use the following
tests, as applicable: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) If the student is enrolled program conducted entirely in his or her native language, the student must take a test
approved under &sect;&sect;668.145 and 668.147(a)(2), or 668.148(b). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) If the student is enrolled in a program that is taught in English with an ESL component, and the student is enrolled
in that program and the ESL component, the student must take either an ESL test approved under &sect;668.147(b), or
a test in the student's native language approved under &sect;668.145, 668.147 or 668.148. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) If the student is enrolled in a program that is taught in English without an ESL component, or the student does not
enroll in the ESL component if the institution offers such a component, the student must take a test in English approved
under &sect;668.145. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4) If the student enrolls in an ESL program, the student must take an ESL test approved under &sect;668.147(b). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Persons with disabilities. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(1) An institution shall use a test described in &sect;&sect;668.147(a)(3) or 668.148(a) for a student with a documented
impairment who has neither a high school diploma nor its equivalent and who is applying for Title IV, HEA program funds.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) The test must reflect the student's skills, knowledge, and general learned abilities rather than reflect the
student's impairment. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) The institution shall document that a student is disabled and unable to be evaluated by the use of a conventional
test from the list of tests approved by the Secretary. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4) Documentation of a student's impairment may be satisfied by_
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(i) A written determination including a diagnosis and recommended testing accommodations by a licensed psychologist
or medical physician; or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(ii) A record of such a determination by an elementary or secondary school or a vocational rehabilitation agency including
a diagnosis and recommended testing accommodations. 
